name: Kirsten Dunst
summary: Kirsten Dunst, known for her roles in "Spider-Man" and "Civil War," has recently spoken out about her experiences in the film industry. In a British GQ interview, she expressed that acquiring roles is not difficult, but that many scripts are of low quality. She also revealed in an interview with The Telegraph that she has worked with "totally improper" male directors who have made inappropriate remarks. Additionally, Dunst admitted to the BBC that she did not advocate for equal pay in the past. Despite these challenges, Dunst has continued to succeed in the industry. In an interview with Variety, she discussed the "miserable" experience of filming the iconic kiss in "Spider-Man," which involved using a "book of famous kisses" for inspiration. The Independent and IGN also highlighted Dunst's comments about the kiss being "miserable." Deadline and Radio Times added details, describing the kiss as "almost like resuscitating" Tobey Maguire. Digital Spy emphasized that the filming was "miserable," while WWD focused on Dunst's fashion choices at a recent premiere.

name: Paula Vennells
summary: New revelations have emerged implicating Paula Vennells, the former head of the Post Office, in the Horizon IT scandal that led to wrongful convictions of subpostmasters. A secret recording reveals Vennells was aware of allegations that the Horizon system could be remotely accessed, despite her previous denials before MPs. She was also warned not to cover up these issues as subpostmasters were being convicted based on the faulty system. An exclusive briefing also suggests Vennells knew about a "covert operations team" that could alter subpostmaster accounts without their knowledge. These recordings contradict Vennells' prior claims that she was unaware of any problems with Horizon until 2015. Following these revelations, Vennells has been stripped of her CBE and has resigned from her position as a non-executive director of the NHS.
